The Digital Ambassador project is designed to build essential digital skills across five key areas. Module 1 focuses on digital literacy awareness by creating an infographic that explains its importance, safe internet practices, and useful tools using platforms like Canva. Module 2 emphasizes building a professional digital presence through platforms such as GitHub and LinkedIn, helping students prepare for future academic and career opportunities. Module 3 introduces coding and collaboration tools like HackerRank and Google Forms to enhance problem-solving and teamwork skills. Module 4 develops professional communication by teaching email etiquette and responsible social media behavior. Finally, Module 5 raises awareness about cybercrime, guiding students to understand online threats and adopt safe digital practices. Together, these modules equip students with the knowledge and skills required to navigate the digital world responsibly and effectively.
Digital Ambassador Project Report
Task 1: Digital Literacy Awareness Infographic (Module 1)
I created my infographic using Canva, as it provides easy-to-use templates and design elements. My design explains the concept of digital literacy, including its importance in academics and daily life. It also highlights three key areas: safe internet practices, useful digital tools for students, and email etiquette. I used icons, short bullet points, and a clean layout to ensure the information is visually appealing and easy to understand.
One interesting aspect of this task was learning how to simplify complex ideas into short, meaningful points suitable for an infographic. However, I found it slightly difficult to balance design and content — making sure the infographic was not too crowded while still including all important information. Overall, this task helped me understand how visual communication can improve awareness and engagement among students.

Task 2: Student Digital Portfolio (Module 2)
For my digital portfolio, I created profiles on GitHub, LinkedIn, and Kaggle. GitHub is mainly used for sharing code and projects, and I created a profile README with my basic academic details and learning goals. LinkedIn is a professional networking platform where I added my education details to build my online presence. Kaggle is useful for data science practice and competitions.
Over the next four years, I plan to use GitHub to upload my academic and personal projects, LinkedIn to connect with professionals and explore internship opportunities, and Kaggle to improve my analytical and problem-solving skills. This task helped me realize the importance of maintaining a professional digital identity early in my career.

Task 3: Coding & Collaboration Platforms (Module 3)
For the coding practice part, I used HackerRank and completed a beginner-level problem. This helped me understand basic problem-solving and how coding platforms evaluate solutions. For collaboration, I used Google Forms to create a Digital Literacy Awareness Quiz with five questions, including multiple-choice and short-answer types.
This task was helpful because it introduced me to practical tools used in academics. Coding platforms will help me strengthen my programming skills through regular practice, while Google Forms can be used for surveys, quizzes, and data collection in projects. These tools will support my academic journey by improving both technical and organizational skills.

Task 4: Professional Email & Etiquette (Module 4)

This module helped me understand the importance of clear and professional communication. A situation where poor digital communication can cause problems is when a student sends an email to a professor without a proper subject line or greeting. This may result in the email being ignored or misunderstood.

Such issues can be avoided by using a clear subject line, maintaining a polite tone, and structuring the email properly. Including a proper greeting and sign-off also ensures professionalism. This task taught me that even simple communication, like emails, plays a crucial role in creating a positive impression in academic and professional environments.

Task 5: Cybercrime Awareness (Module 5)

While researching cybercrime, I was most surprised by how common phishing and online payment fraud have become, especially among students. Many attacks happen due to lack of awareness and simple mistakes like clicking unknown links or sharing OTPs.

As a result of this task, one habit I will change is being more cautious while handling online transactions and verifying the authenticity of websites and messages before taking any action. This module made me more aware of digital risks and the importance of staying alert online.

